docs.abstract: The holiest day in the Christian calendar comes as the church-filled city is in a heated political debate, and still deep in grief.
docs.snippet: The holiest day in the Christian calendar comes as the church-filled city is in a heated political debate, and still deep in grief.
docs.lead_paragraph: Less than two weeks after the shooting of six people at a small Christian school in Nashville, the city’s raw mourning was swept into sprawling, emotional protests and political strife, culminating in accusations of racism over the expulsion of two young Black state legislators. It has been an extraordinary and painful season of hugs and funerals, marches and speeches, tears and anger.

docs.abstract: Fruit can be fresh. So can style, the country air and an impertinent teenage boy.
docs.snippet: Fruit can be fresh. So can style, the country air and an impertinent teenage boy.
docs.lead_paragraph: One of the first appearances of “fresh” in The New York Times was in a letter to the editor in 1858. Under the headline “Pursuit of Fresh Air Under Difficulties,” a reader traveling to a vacation home in upstate New York described the pungent smells of the city: the milk factory’s “stump-tail odor,” the gas works that “dispense a large part of their product in the surrounding atmosphere.” The writer, who signed as “Olfactorius,” awaited relief in the country: “I think no one will dispute that I deserve all the fresh breezes that I get after passing through the frightful variety of bad smells.”

headline.main: Fresh Meanings for a Common Word

docs.lead_paragraph: What started out looking like an almost reverential treatment — at least by “Saturday Night Live” standards — of the Easter holiday quickly gave way to a satirical monologue from former President Donald J.
